Introduction¶

Using this data set from kaggle that contains over 25k+ soccer matches from around the world, I want to analyze soccer goal-scoring trends. This involves sifting through all the match data that has been given to us, deciding what is relevant, formatting the relevant data in a way that we can easily analyze, and then effectively communicating our results. The questions I want to tackle are:

  • What type of goals are scored and what are their relative distributions? Does this vary based on the country?
  • Which player has scored the most penalty kicks?
  • Who has scored more goals, Messi or Ronaldo? How does the goal distribution for each of these players differ from one another?

Let's first import all the packages that we'll want to use

Cleaning the Data¶

As we can see from the tables above, there is a lot of irrelevant data for our purposes. Thus we will have to figure out what is important and what isn't, and then we can format our data in such a way that we can easily analyze it

Straight off the bat we see that "match_df" is the most relevant dataset for our questions and it is also the biggest. However, a lot of this information is stuff we don't care about so lets focus only on what we need. Let's go ahead and drop all the player position columns (as we don't care about formations), and let's drop the betting stats (as we don't care about betting odds either)

In [897]:
# Find the length of the column goal. Used as iteration length
length = range(len(match_df1['goal']))
In [898]:
# Finds all goal scorers and stores them in a list called "all_scorers"
all_scorers = []
for i in length:
    player_id = []
    match_str1 = match_df1.iloc[i,33]
    for c in range(len(match_str1)):
        if c < (len(match_str1)-7) and c >= 1:
            if match_str1[c:(c+7)] == 'player1' and match_str1[c-1] != '/':
                end = match_str1.index('<',c+8)
                player = match_str1[(c+8):end]
                player_id.append(player)
    
    # Use this block if you want to have unknown goal scorers in there
    total_goals = (match_df1.iloc[i,9]+ match_df1.iloc[i,10])
    if (len(player_id) != total_goals):
        diff = total_goals - len(player_id)
        for i in range(diff):
            player_id.append("unknown")
    
    all_scorers.append(player_id)
In [900]:
#Finds goal types and stores them in a list called "all_goaltypes"
all_goaltypes = []
for i in length:
    match_str1 = match_df1.iloc[i,33]
    shot_id = []
    for c in range(len(match_str1)):
        if c < (len(match_str1)-7) and c >= 1:
            if match_str1[c:(c+7)] == 'subtype' and match_str1[c-1] != '/':
                end = match_str1.index('<',c)
                shot = match_str1[(c+8):end]
                shot_id.append(shot)
        if c < (len(match_str1)-9) and c >= 1:
            if match_str1[c:(c+9)] == 'penalties' and match_str1[c-1] != '/':
                shot_id.append('penalties')
            if match_str1[c:(c+8)] == 'owngoals' and match_str1[c-1] != '/':
                shot_id.append('owngoals')
    
    # Use this block if you want to have unknown goal scorers in there
    #total_goals = (match_df1.iloc[i,9]+ match_df1.iloc[i,10])
    total_goals = len(all_scorers[i])
    if (len(shot_id) != total_goals):
        diff = total_goals - len(shot_id)
        for i in range(diff):
            shot_id.append("unknown")
    all_goaltypes.append(shot_id)

Now that we have our scorer data and what type of goal it was, we just need to format it in a way that will be easy to work with!¶

To answer our questions in the smoothest way possible, let's create a new dataframe called "df_goals" that countains the player who scored the goal, what country they play in, and what type of goal it was.

This is not as straightforward as just looking at each individual row because each game could have multiple goals with various corresponding goal types. So first lets expand this data out so that each row only contains the information for a single goal

# Expanding on the information contained in these two columns. The result will be 3 lists that describe

player_list = []
goal_list = []
for i in length:
    if (len(goal_types.iloc[i,0]) == len(goal_types.iloc[i,1])):
        for l in range(len(goal_types.iloc[i,0])):
            player_list.append(goal_types.iloc[i,0][l])

Now that all our data is recorded cleanly in a table, we can analyze the data. Considering that the data is a spread of about 20 categories and we want to see their distribution, a pie or bar chart would be best to analyze this data. I went with a pie chart for visual asthetic. Let's also drop the "unkown" goals, as these add no value to our findings (although they are a substantial percentage of the recorded goals)

Exploratory Data Analysis¶

Q1) What does the scoring breakdown look like? Does it differ between countries? Are there any anomallys in the data?¶

In [1565]:
# Drop unknown goal types
df = df[df.goal_type != 'unknown']

# Get data values and labels for pie chart
data = df['goal_type'].value_counts()
labels = df['goal_type'].value_counts().index.tolist()

# Percentage of total will be used for a numerical answer
percent = 100.*data/data.sum()
labels = ['{0} - {1:1.2f} %'.format(i,j) for i,j in zip(labels, percent)]

# Plot the pie chart for the data
plt.figure(figsize=(20,10));
plt.pie(data);
plt.legend(labels, loc='upper right', bbox_to_anchor=(-0.1, 1.), fontsize=15);
plt.title("All Soccer Scoring Distribution");

We finally have a visual on our data! We can use this as a base metric to judge the individual countries distributions¶

Now let's repeat this same process to get a pie chart graphic for each country and look at their distributions!

In [1564]:
# Group the data by the country name
grouped_goals = df.groupby('name')

# Print out a pie chart with 
for i in grouped_goals.groups.keys():
    temp = grouped_goals.get_group(i)
    data = temp['goal_type'].value_counts()
    labels1 = temp['goal_type'].value_counts().index.tolist()
    percent = 100.*data/data.sum()
    labels = ['{0} - {1:1.2f} %'.format(i,j) for i,j in zip(labels1, percent)]

    plt.figure(figsize=(20,10));
    plt.pie(data);
    plt.title(i + " Scoring stats");
    plt.legend(labels, loc='upper right', bbox_to_anchor=(-0.1, 1.), fontsize=10);

From looking at the data above we notice a few things straight away¶

  • France has the largest percentage of goals scored by penalties by quite some distance. France has over 17% of it's recorded goals while the average is about 11.5%. As to why this percentage is so much higher we cannot gather from the data given to us. Some possible reasons could be that the refs are more strict in france, the players dive more, or that the defenders make more aggressive challenges in the box.
  • Shots are the most common way to score across the board. This isn't super surprising as most goals are scored via shooting the ball than headers, tap ins, etc..
  • On average there are more own goals scored than volleys! This is surprising to me because i always figured own goals were an anomoly that were few and far between. But it appears that own goals are the 5th most common type of goal, coming in at about 4.3% of goals scored on average!
  • France has nearly double the average percentage of own goals scored. Perhaps there are a lot of defensive errors in French soccer that one could look into. This would be hard to analyze given our data
  • The Netherlands have nearly double the average percentage of distance goals scored. Perhaps the players are more willing to shoot from distance or maybe defenses are more compact in this league, meaning players have to shoot from further away. Once again more investigation would be required. We could go about this by looking at the formations of teams in the netherlands, and look for trends among Dutch teams that make them hard to break down in the final third. We could also look at players' FIFA shot ratings, and see if the average Dutch player has a "good" leg for taking longshots

Q2) Which player has the most penalties scored?¶

This involves doing a few things with our data

  • First, we can drop all the penalties scored by players with an unknown id. If we don't know who scored the goal then it isn't useful for our data
  • Next we need to merge our data set with player_df so that we will be able to see the player name rather than just the id. We want to see who the player with the most goals acutally is after all
  • Finally we can drop the irrelevant columns from our new joined dataset. This includes the columns like id (for the country), height, and weight of the player. Store all of this in a new table titled df2

# This block of code is filling in 2 lists: One with the player name and one with his associated number of pks scored

    temp = grouped_players.get_group(i)
    pens.append(len(temp['goal_type']))
    names.append(temp.iloc[0,4])

By looking at the differences in this table we notice a few things:

  • Ronalldo has approximately double the amount of goals off headers compared to Messi. We could query the heights for each of these players and we see that Messi is much shorter than ronaldo. Do taller players on average score more headed goals? This is another trend we could investigate in order to try and explain why ronaldo has more headed goals.
  • Messi has scored about 40 more shot goals than Ronaldo. Unfortunately, in order to understand why this occured this would involve looking at more information about each shot that we don't have.



Conclusions¶

Through analyzing the type of goals in this dataset we have found many interesting things. First we saw what the goal breakdown looked like across the world and then compared that to what the goal breakdown looked like for each country's league. We were able to see a couple surprising stats, such as the fact that France has an exceptionally large percentage of penalty kick goals and that on average 4.3% of goals scored are own goals. Personally, I would have imagined the own goal rate to be much lower.

Follwing this we found out that Ronaldo leads the world in penalty kick goals (49) and that Messi has scored more goals than Ronaldo overall (293 to 290). We were also able to see how Messi's goal distribution differed from Ronaldo's.

We were limited in a few ways with our questions. For example, when we were analyzing how the type of goals scored differ based off the country, we were not able to clearly point out why. We showed that France has a much higher percentage of own goals scored and were able to hypothesize a few theories, but we would need to gather more data and investigate further if we wanted to find out why this percentage is so high. In the same way, we can hypothesize that the types of goals Ronaldo scores are different from the types of goals that Messi scores due to their physical differences, but more investigation would be required to attribute this as the main reason.
